ce:section.ce:para:
Fishery commodities are more likely to be contaminated by pathogens. Therefore, the performance of detecting pathogens in fresh fish samples is very important. In this study, we tested the applicability of FRET-based paper sensor with smartphone to detect V. parahaemolyticus in cod samples. As could be seen in Fig. 6
                        A, fluorescence color of our proposed paper sensor in cod samples was dependent on the concentration of V. parahaemolyticus, and the B/R value of the paper sensor was inversely proportional to the concentration of the target bacteria at 102-106 cfu/mL (Fig. 6B), with a linear relationship of B/R = −0.51 log [V. parahaemolyticus (cfu/mL)] + 4.53 (correlation coefficient R2 = 0.9771, Fig. 6C), and a detection limit of 6.1 × 101 cfu/mL. Our strategy was portable and acceptably sensitive compared to other reported sensor for the detection of V. parahaemolyticus (Table 1
                        ). From the results, we concluded that the FRET-based paper sensor with smartphone prepared was able to detect the concentration of V. parahaemolyticus in seafood samples with high sensitivity.
